However, he said it was wrong to assume it would mean their party would have a permanent majority at Westminster. Lord Forsyth, who was Scottish Secretary in Sir John Major’s Government, said: “There are number of foolish people in the Conservative Party in the south who are keen on independence or ‘Devo max’ (devolution of all tax powers). “Labour thought by creating devolution they would have permanent power in Scotland. I don’t think political parties can establish support by trying to gerrymander the constitution – the voters are smarter than that.”
He also attacked those, including David Cameron, who are promising voters to devolve extra powers to Scotland if voters reject separation next year, arguing this would also harm the Union. Do you think Scotland should vote for independence if it gives the Tories a majority in Westminster?
Henry McLeish, a former Labour Scottish First Minister, said independence would be a “sizeable hit” on the electoral ambitions of Ed Miliband and his sucdessors. “It’s obvious when you consider that the Scottish MPs for a very large part of the Labour group at Westminster,” the former Central Fife MP said. “In the short term independence would have a huge impact, a massive impact on the political dynamic.”
Labour strategists and election experts argued that a general election victory would still possible after independence, pointing out that Tony Blair won three contests with a majority of seats in England and Wales. They said the Tories are failing to make much headway in the North of England and predicted this would become the “new Scotland” if the latter decided to leave the Union. John McTernan, who was political secretary to Tony Blair at Number 10, was optimist about Labour’s chances even if Scots do vote to separate. “Since 1987 the Tories have been losing votes in the cities and the North. They are becoming confined to the South and the country,” he said. “If Scotland left, the North would become the new Scotland.”
He said a vote for independence would also be a “massive psychological blow” to the authority Mr Cameron and George Osborne as they would have overseen the break-up of the UK. This may lead to the British Nationalist elements of the Conservative Party defecting to Ukip, he claimed. John Curtice, professor of politics at Strathclyde University, cited the trio of Blair victories as evidence Scottish independence would “make it difficult but not impossible” for Labour to win future general elections. However, he said the party’s hopes would be harmed by a future boundary review as the electoral system in England is biased towards Labour. The debate over Labour’s prospects came after Sir John Major said during a recent press gallery lunch that the Conservatives “would be better off without Scotland” but the UK would not. Scotland
